text: This movie may be fine as a cinematic experience, but as history it's awful. Applying a typical heroic arc belittles the actual story of Nat Turner. The movie, instead of being used as just a political commentary to "rise up" as they infuse pictures of BLM into their trailer, could have told the actual story of Nat Turner and let the viewer decide how to interpret the actions of a controversial figure. Instead the director decides to justify his plight to us without letting us decide, gladly setting up the brutal treatment he received from his masters while skipping over the unfortunate parts where he himself killed defenseless women and children. The story of Nat Turner is one that deserves to be told, but not politicized, and the themes of the aftermath of his rebellion should not be glossed over, where white folks, slave owning or not, became so terrified of similar rebellions, Turner's actions actually significantly made worse the treatment of slaves throughout the south for 30 years until it's eventual forceful abolition. Was Turner's Rebellion a good thing for slaves? Were his actions justified? These are all complicated questions that a better director would've raised.

text: Nat Turner's rebellion was a vicious affair that helped justify enslavement. It, along with the slave revolts and subsequent genocide of whites in Haiti, helped fuel anti-abolitionist attitudes and cause the Civil War. It was not an option to free a tiger that you had by the tail, as people believed. Any move in that direction terrified many southern whites, slaveholders or not. You can argue that it's slave propaganda as the source if you want, but apparently the order was to "kill all white people" and that's what they did. If you're gonna educate yourself, educate yourself right. Abolitionists in the north and south did not use events like Nat Turner's rebellion to argue for the freeing of slaves. It cemented a belief in the opposite. It's ironic that this movie names itself that. Because an extremely popular movie by the same name made 100 years ago dealt with the same topic but with rather different conclusions.

We never should drown history, and we should always be skeptical as to what lens you are learning it from. But that is not enough, we need to encourage our children to read for themselves and spend their own time learning... I wish I had more time to write but at the moment I do not. I will just end this by saying please... Please do not be just another wedge of division among human beings which every one of us is. Humanity is far more complex than "black people did this" white people did that" "but they did that and this and blah bah". Learn the history and use it to make the future more united, not to fill your heart with hatred.

text: OH. MY. GOD. You guys have no clue why this film is so important. It's a direct response to "The birth of a Nation" by David W. Griffith, one of the first cinematographers and the most important one in terms of story-telling. Griffith's film made it's debut on 1915 and it told the story of an ultra-glamorized KKK versus wrongly portrayed black people (played by white actors with black paint all over their bodies). It was the first big-buster film in history and the most racist one too. This is the first thing they teach you in film school, and if i was mad when i read about it i can't imagine how Nate Parker must have felt when he did. The fact that he made this film and entitled it with the SAME NAME is just the perfect response to the injustice and racism in America's film history.

text: This is a biased movie about a very controversial individual.  The movie doesn't show Nate Turner and his partners killing children or old people.  One can argue that he was fighting against oppression and that it was slave owners' violence that made him snap.  Yet there's the fact that the movie portray him as being influenced by a passage of the Bible, which makes him a radical religious individual, very close to a Muslim Jihadist.  Okay. there was a lot of violence against black slaves back then, yet the movie claims that a passage of the Bible served as justification for his acts : that's religious extremist terrorism.  Let's talk about another movie now : The Last Samurai starring Tom Cruise. The movie came to being as the US  was fighting terrorists or terrorist sympathizers in Afghanistan. The Tom Cruise character goes to Japan, becomes a prisoner of the Japanese, falls in love with their ways, and then fights along the Japanese against American Troops. What does that make his character? The answer would be very close to the American Al-Qaeda, the white guy who was captured fighting among them.  I would say that, even though a lot of people can defend it as a work of art, this kind of movie is very, very dangerous since there's a lot of viewers who don't have the maturity of the knowledge of context in order to view it for what it is, a biased artistic interpretation of a historic event, and not as a piece of propaganda supporting extreme views and actions.

text: Today is the anniversary of Nat Turner's slave rebellion on August 21, 1831. Deeply religious, Nat saw a solar eclipse earlier that year in February, much like the one we will see today, as a sign from God to rise up and revolt against every slave-owning family that crossed their path in Southampton County, Virginia. "Turner gathered more supportersâ€”growing to a group of up to 40 or 50 slavesâ€”as he and his men continued their violent spree through the county." An estimated 55 men, women, and children were killed in the rebellion." The rebellion only lasted 48 hours as it was quickly suppressed. Afterwards, while Turner was in hiding, an estimated 200 slaves were murdered in revenge for the rebellion. Nat Turner was soon captured and hung, but his actions put so much fear into the hearts of Southerners ending the emancipation movement in the region. "Turner's actions also added fuel to the abolitionist movement in the north." Born into slavery, they chose to fight back, they chose to be free.
